This method returns *&quot;a list of Futures holding their status and results **when all complete**&quot;*, i.e. it is **blocking** and that&#39;s what we need in this case (we are not interested in its return value and it&#39;s omitted in the code below).

`invokeAll()` expects a collection of `Callable` and we can use [`Executors.callable()`](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/concurrent/Executors.html#callable(java.lang.Runnable)) to convert a `Runnable` into a `Callable`.

